Â§1. ADHD ACROSS CULTURES (Attention-Deficit/Hyperactivity Disorder)

1.1 ADHD in Global Flow Context

Cultural variations in ADHD expression:

Â· Western contexts: Hyperactivity more recognized
Â· Asian contexts: Inattentive type more common (often misunderstood as "daydreaming")
Â· Latin American contexts: Often attributed to "nervios" or spiritual causes
Â· African contexts: May be seen as behavioral issue rather than neurological

Universal Flow response: Structure work around interests, allow movement and multiple projects. Body Doubling and visual schedules boost focus.

1.2 Culturally Adapted ADHD Practices

Â· Meeting structures that respect cultural time perceptions (flexible vs. punctual)
Â· Movement allowances that don't violate cultural norms (subtle fidgeting vs. obvious movement)
Â· Communication styles adapted to cultural expectations (direct vs. indirect)
Â· Family involvement appropriate to cultural family structures

1.3 Medication Across Cultures

Â· Western approach: Often medication-first
Â· European approach: More environmental adaptations
Â· Asian contexts: Stigma around psychiatric medication
Â· Flow principle: Medication optional, never mandatory. Combine with environmental support.

1.4 Global Resource Mapping for ADHD

```
ADHD Support = Local Resources + Global Knowledge + Cultural Adaptation
```

