Â§2. AUTISM SPECTRUM WORLDWIDE

2.1 Autism in Cultural Context

Cultural variations in autism understanding:

Â· Western medical model: Spectrum, deficits-focused
Â· East Asian: Often hidden, family responsibility
Â· Global South: May be seen through spiritual/religious lens
Â· Indigenous: Sometimes recognized as different way of being

Flow approach: Celebrate neurocognitive diversity while providing necessary support.

2.2 Cultural Adaptation of Autism Support

Â· Communication styles: Adapt to cultural communication norms
Â· Social expectations: Balance cultural social demands with autistic needs
Â· Family systems: Work with extended family structures where relevant
Â· Community integration: Find culturally appropriate ways to participate

2.3 Special Interests as Cultural Bridges

Special interests can:

Â· Preserve cultural knowledge (history, traditions)
Â· Innovate within cultural contexts
Â· Bridge cultural gaps through shared passions

2.4 Masking & Cultural Conformity

The double burden:

Â· Masking neurodivergent traits
Â· PLUS masking cultural differences (for immigrants/minorities)

Flow solution: Create spaces where multiple authenticities can coexist.

